The "avocado belt" in the Mexican Republic includes Michoacán and the State of Mexico[5]. The main varieties in Mexico are Fuerte, Hass, Bacon, Reed, Criollor and Zutano[6]. The avocado comes from Central Mexico, where its ancient history based on archaeological Claude Earl Smith, Jr., who discovered that avocado cotyledons found in the deposits of the Coxcatlán cave in Tehuacan, Puebla, date back to about 10,000 years ago. The remains of primitive avocado trees survived in the state of Nuevo León. other countries in North and South America, including the United States.